# Reflection on GitHub and Project Planning

## What did you learn about GitHub and project planning?
Throughout this assignment, I discovered that while GitHub is a powerful tool for source code management and collaborative work, its interface can often be frustrating and not as intuitive as one might hope. I found that the frequent use of common words with new, specialized meanings—such as "issues" and "discussions"—adds a layer of confusion that complicates the planning process. Although GitHub provides a robust set of functionalities for version control, task tracking, and project management, the overall user experience left me feeling that it is more cumbersome than necessary. This exercise highlighted both the strengths and weaknesses of GitHub from a practical standpoint, making me more aware of the trade-offs between its extensive features and the complexity of its interface.

## What was challenging or fun?
The assignment was predominantly challenging rather than fun. The most difficult aspect was navigating through GitHub’s user interface to set up issues, branches, and pull requests efficiently. Each step—from creating tasks and assigning labels to making coherent commits and merging branches—felt like an uphill battle against unintuitive design choices. The repeated need to adapt to unfamiliar terminology and workflows was more taxing than enjoyable. Although I did learn some valuable skills, such as the importance of clear commit messages and the practical use of pull requests for merging changes, the overall process was a struggle. It was an experience that I hope not to revisit frequently, especially since it did not live up to the expectation of being a rewarding or engaging learning opportunity.

## If you had more time, what would you improve?
With more time, I would focus on revisiting and improving the implementation of task 3 regarding branch management and pull requests. I feel that my approach to creating feature branches, committing changes, and finally merging them via pull requests might not have been optimal. Extra time would allow me to better plan and execute the branching strategy, ensure that all commit messages are as clear and descriptive as possible, and refine the pull request process. Additionally, I would consider exploring alternative approaches or tools that might offer a more streamlined and user-friendly experience for project planning and collaboration.
